<p>As epidemic outbreaks emerge, their transmission dynamics can vary much depending on the geographical locations of the initial infection [
 <xref rid="pone.0234619.ref014" ref-type="bibr">14</xref>, 
 <xref rid="pone.0234619.ref023" ref-type="bibr">23</xref>]. This maybe the most important insight from the recent, data-driven research on epidemics in urban populations [
 <xref rid="pone.0234619.ref013" ref-type="bibr">13</xref>, 
 <xref rid="pone.0234619.ref014" ref-type="bibr">14</xref>, 
 <xref rid="pone.0234619.ref024" ref-type="bibr">24</xref>]. We chose a metapopulation model, that can capture such effects. In an entirely susceptible population at location 
 <italic>i</italic> at time 
 <italic>t</italic>, an outbreak happens with probability: 
